    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "*Hmph.* \"Goblin mischief\"? It's just... the way things *are*, friend. You can't separate the physiology from the sheer, chaotic energy of the world, and goblins are the purest embodiment of that chaotic energy! They are the biological equivalent of a poorly maintained, yet highly energetic, fermentation vat.\n\nBut fine, fine. We'll stick to the sterile, textbook biology, though I warn you, it lacks the satisfying *clatter* of a goblin raid.\n\nTo address your core question: both mechanical tension and metabolic stress are hypothesized to signal the muscle to initiate **protein synthesis** (the building process).\n\n**Mechanical Tension** directly signals through the structural integrity of the sarcomeres. When you apply high tension, you cause micro-trauma to the muscle fibers. This damage, or the intense strain itself, activates mechanosensors within the muscle cell. These sensors then trigger signaling cascades—think of it like a very sophisticated, very stressed-out alarm system in the muscle—that ultimately upregulate the pathways responsible for muscle protein synthesis, often involving pathways like mTOR. It's the \"structural repair\" signal.\n\n**Metabolic Stress**, on the other hand, is more",
      "source": "target",
